        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Sandown</placeName>
                    <date>5 Octob. 1870.</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I communicated the wish You expressed to put in Your new work something about the vertebrate character of the Ascidian larva, to my brother and some days ago he sent me a letter to You with some particulars about this question.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> Till then he has not received Your work on the Cirripedia and so could not thank You for it.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I return in three days to London and after a week more we both intent to go to Leipsic for the winter; I hope to see You once more before my departure.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>Yours | Very truly | W. Kovalevsky</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">No letter from CD to Kovalevsky regarding the addition to <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref> has been found; however, Kovalevsky visited the Darwins at some point between 15 August and 1 September 1870 (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7302.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from V. O. Kovalevsky, 15 August [1870]</ref>, and letter from S. V. Kovalevskaya and V. O. Kovalevsky, 1 September 1870). For <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2749.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Alexander Onufrievich Kovalevsky’s</ref> account of ascidian larva forwarded through his brother, see the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7326.xml" resp="#automat">letter from A. O. Kovalevsky, 25 September 1870</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD evidently gave copies of his monographs on living barnacles (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4837.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Living Cirripedia</hi> (1851)</ref> and (1854)) to V. O. Kovalevsky who then sent them to his brother in Naples (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7322.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from V. O. Kovalevsky, 20 September 1870</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Kovalevsky had been in England since mid-August (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7302.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from V. O. Kovalevsky, 15 August [1870]</ref>). He and his wife, Sofia Vasilyevna Kovalevskaya, intended to spend the winter in Leipzig, Germany. For Kovalevsky’s previous visit to Down, see n. 1, above.</note>
        </div>        
            
